{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2499"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2499"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.06,0.24,0.03,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55597"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2499"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41137"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1925"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"12752"},{"type":"tags","id":"12756"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16977"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55597"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old Indigenous woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of ankle swelling and dark urine. She has a medical history of an infected cut on her arm about three weeks ago. She takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 162/94 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is peripheral oedema of the lower limbs. Urinalysis reveals blood +++ and protein +++. Urine albumin creatinine ratio is 100 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3). Urine microscopy shows dysmorphic red blood cells and hyaline casts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most specific for the likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nephrotic range proteinuria","Hypertension","Hyaline casts on urine microscopy","Sub-nephrotic range proteinuria","Dysmorphic red blood cells on urine microscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (PSGN), given her recent history of infection, the timing of symptom onset, and the urinary findings. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysmorphic red blood cells on urine microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E are highly specific for glomerulonephritis, especially of a nephritic nature. Their presence indicates that the source of bleeding is glomerular rather than from the lower urinary tract. The dysmorphic shape is caused by red blood cells passing through damaged glomeruli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrotic range proteinuria\u003C/strong\u003E (\u0026gt;3.5 g proteinuria per day) is not present in this case. The patient\u0027s urine albumin creatinine ratio of 100 mg/mmol indicates significant proteinuria but falls into the \u003Cstrong\u003Esub-nephrotic range\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis can present with sub-nephrotic range proteinuria, this finding is present in many nephrotic-type glomerulonephritis\u0027, which typically do not feature haematuria. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is a common finding in acute glomerulonephritis due to fluid retention and activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. However, it is not specific to glomerulonephritis and can occur in many other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E are formed from Tamm-Horsfall protein and can be seen in healthy individuals and in the setting of dehydration. They are not specific for glomerulonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the context of PSGN, other important findings include a recent history of streptococcal infection (typically 1-3 weeks prior), elevated anti-streptolysin O titre (ASOT), and low C3 complement levels. The presence of red cell casts (not mentioned in this case) would be even more specific for glomerulonephritis than dysmorphic red blood cells alone. Management typically involves supportive care, as most cases of PSGN are self-limiting in young, otherwise healthy individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysmorphic red blood cells and red blood cell casts on urine microscopy are highly specific for glomerulonephritis, especially of a nephritic nature.","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis typically presents 1-3 weeks after a streptococcal infection, often in young adults."],"references":["Hashmi MS, Pandey J. Nephritic Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562240/#:~:text=The%20nephritic%20syndrome%20is%20a,be%20promptly%20diagnosed%20and%20managed."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41137"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2499"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41137"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T22:18:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T22:19:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2499"}},"content":{